      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey! I’m glad you’re looking into remodeling your kitchen—that’s a big, beautiful project, and knocking down a wall can really open up the space. To determine if a wall is load‑bearing, you’ll want to check a few things: look at the floor plan, inspect the wall’s thickness and the presence of a header, and maybe even consult a structural engineer or a local building code official.\n\n**Here’s a quick guide:**\n\n1. **Check the floor plan** – Most architects label load‑bearing walls in the original plans. If you don’t have them, a local architect or engineer can pull up the original docs or create a new one.\n\n2. **Inspect the wall itself** – Load‑bearing walls are often thicker (around 6–8 inches) and may have a horizontal “header” above or below them that transfers the load. If you see a solid, thick wall with a horizontal beam, it’s likely load‑bearing.\n\n3. **Look for a “sister” wall** – In many homes, a load‑bearing wall will have a “sister” wall on the other side that’s also thick. This is a good sign that the wall is part of",
