      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey! The attic connection is a great question, and it’s a classic way to confirm whether a wall is truly load‑bearing. To check if the roof weight rests on that specific wall, you can look at the framing in the attic, trace the roof rafters or trusses, and see where they intersect with the wall.\n\n**Here’s how to investigate:**\n\n1. **Look at the attic framing** – If you climb up (or call a contractor), you’ll see the roof’s structural members. In most homes, the rafters or trusses will either rest directly on the top plate of the wall or on a beam that sits on the wall. If the rafters line up with the wall’s top plate, that wall is likely carrying the roof load.\n\n2. **Check for a “sister” beam** – Often, a load‑bearing wall will have a horizontal beam (called a “sister” beam) that runs across the top of the wall. This beam will be anchored to the wall’s top plate, and it will transfer the roof weight down to the foundation. If you see a beam that’s clearly attached to the wall’s top, that’s a strong sign it’s load‑",
